When two CSS rules are in conflict, it is resolved using the concept of specificity
More specific the selector, higher the preference
Hierarchy (from highest specificity to lowest)
Inline Styles
ID Selectors
Class Selectors
Element Selectors
When selectors of equal Specificity are in conflict - Lower (or latest) rule in the stylesheet wins
CODE DEMO:
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <title>Activity</title>
    <style>
      main {
        background-color: red;
      }
      .main {
        background-color: blue;
      }
      #main {
        background-color: green;
      }
    </style>
  </head>
  <body>
    <main class="main" id="main" style="background-color: yellow;">
      <p>This is a para inside child</p>
    </main>
  </body>
</html>

Specificity Order in CSS

Inline styles (inside the style="" attribute) → highest priority

ID selectors (#main) → priority 100

Class selectors (.main) → priority 10

Element selectors (main) → priority 1

So here:

main { background: red; } → lowest priority

.main { background: blue; } → higher than element

#main { background: green; } → higher than class

style="background-color: yellow;" → highest priority → final winner ✅

✅ Final Output:

The <main> element will have a yellow background because inline style overrides everything else.
_______________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

2.lets check->>>>>>>>>>>>>>
HTML
 <section class="parent">
   <div class="child">
     <p>This is a para inside child</p>
   </div>
 </section>
CSS
.parent {
   color: steelblue;
   background-color: lightcyan;
}
What happens here:

The <section> with class parent has:

Text color: steelblue

Background color: lightcyan

Since text color (color) is inherited, the <p> inside .child will also appear in steelblue.

The background color (background-color) is not inherited, so only the .parent element’s area will have lightcyan.
The .child <div> will have transparent background (default), so it shows the parent’s lightcyan.

✅ Output: You’ll see a lightcyan box with text "This is a para inside child" in steelblue.
